  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_3' aria-label=\" Dr. Poornima Advani & Anr versus Government of NCT & Anr. pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('3','2025','2025_2_1178_1205','2025INSC262'); ><font size='4'> <strong>DR. POORNIMA ADVANI & ANR<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>GOVERNMENT OF NCT & ANR. </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 2 S.C.R. 1178</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 262</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010003042025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : J.B. PARDIWALA, R MAHADEVAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether in the facts and circumstances of the case, the Appellants would be entitled to claim interest on delayed stamp duty refund, in the absence of a provision in the statute to that effect. Headnotes&dagger; Constitution of India, 1950 &ndash; Article 226 &ndash; Refund along with the principal: Held: The Appellants approached the High Court under Article 226 of the Constitution following their request for refund of the stamp duty as the e-stamp paper purchased by the Appellants was misplaced &ndash; The Single Judge of the High Court passed an order<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 18-02-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CIVIL APPEAL No. 2643/2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Disposed off</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_2_1178_1205','2025INSC262','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('3','2025','2025_